fields.instruction:
1. The online test contains 65 questions.
  2. Test duration: 95 minutes.
  3. This test contains:
  • Mathematical Ability - 10 questions
  • Analytical Ability- 15 questions
  • Verbal Ability - 40 questions
  1. Do not press the back button or refresh the web page.
  2. Every question is single correct.
  3. To save your answer and move to next question, you MUST click on the Save & Next button.
  4. To mark the question for review, click on the Mark for Review & Next button.
  5. For every correct answer, +4  marks is awarded and -1 for each incorrect response.
  6. Options once marked can  later be changed but cannot be unmarked.
  7. Answer to questions marked for review will automatically be submitted.
  8. As soon as the time ends the test will automatically be submitted.
  9. Anybody found guilty of cheating will be disqualified.
  10. You are allowed to submit the test only once. If you finish the test in any case, you will not be allowed to re-submit the test.

Read the given paragraph and answer the question in the end.

Primitive man was probably more concerned with fire as a source of warmth and as a means of cooking food than as a source of light.  Before he discovered less laborious ways of making fire, he had to preserve it, and whenever he went on a journey he carried a firebrand with him. His discovery that the firebrand, from which the torch may very well have developed, could be used for illumination was probably incidental to the primary purpose of preserving a flame.

Lamps, too, probably developed by accident.  Early man may have had his first conception of a lamp while watching a twig or fibre burning in the molten fat dropped from a roasting carcass.  All he had to do was to fashion a vessel to contain fat and float a lighted reed in it. Such lamps, which are made of hollowed stones or sea shells, have persisted in identical from up to quite recent times.
